{:metadata {:description [{"text" "<p>Lantibiotics are peptide antimicrobials characterized by the unique amino acids lanthionine and methyllanthionine, which are introduced by dehydration of Ser/Thr residues and linkage of the resulting dehydrated amino acids with Cys residues. Members of this family are known generally as LanM, a multifunctional enzyme of lantibiotic biosynthesis [[cite:PUB00064947]]. This catalysis by LanM distinguishes the type 2 lantibiotics, such as lacticin 481,  mersacidin, cinnamycin, and lichenicidin, from LanBC-produced type 1 lantibiotics such as nisin and subtilin.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>The N-terminal domain of LanM enzymes contains regions associated with Ser and Thr dehydration [[cite:PUB00081043]]. The C-terminal region is a LanC-type domain ([interpro:IPR007822]) that catalyses the formation of the lanthionine bridge [[cite:PUB00068008]].</p>", "llm" false, "checked" false, "updated" false}], :is-reviewed-llm false, :representative-structure nil, :overlaps-with nil, :member-databases {"ncbifam" {"TIGR03897" "type 2 lanthipeptide synthetase LanM"}, "cdd" {"cd04792" "Cyclases involved in the biosynthesis of class II lantibiotics, and similar proteins"}, "pirsf" {"PIRSF037228" "Lantibiotic modifying enzyme, RumM type"}}, :is-updated-llm false, :name {"name" "Type 2 lantibiotic biosynthesis protein LanM", "short" "Lanti_2_LanM"}, :wikipedia nil, :source-database "interpro", :type "family", :counters {"structures" 2, "domain_architectures" 0, "proteomes" 561, "taxa" 2969, "subfamilies" 0, "interactions" 0, "matches" 2751, "sets" 0, "proteins" 2726, "structural_models" {"alphafold" 2040}, "pathways" 0}, :integrated nil, :cross-references {}, :set-info nil, :accession "IPR017146", :literature {"PUB00081043" {"URL" nil, "issue" "6", "authors" ["Shimafuji C" "Noguchi M" "Nishie M" "Nagao J" "Shioya K" "Zendo T" "Nakayama J" "Sonomoto K."], "ISO_journal" "J. Biosci. Bioeng.", "DOI_URL" "http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/j.jbiosc.2015.03.020", "medline_jo